      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lodges in Africa</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ralph Weston letter on Michael Korda's May 7 travel article describes to trip to national parks in Kenya and Tanzania (S)o</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: Having recently returned from a trip to national parks in Kenya and Tanzania, I can readily sympathize with Michael Korda's  concern for the overcrowding of East African parks.</p>
        <p>Modern technology exacerbates the problem -- using car phones, the driver-guides are all in constant communication with one another, and the sighting of a lion leads to rapid convergence of every vehicle within electronic earshot. The  animals don't seem to mind, how ever. We watched a mother and cub stroll between the Land Rovers as casually as a pedestrian jaywalking through the cars at a Manhattan intersection.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: Having recently returned from a trip to national parks in Kenya and Tanzania, I can readily sympathize with Michael Korda's  concern for the overcrowding of East African parks.</p>
        <p>Modern technology exacerbates the problem -- using car phones, the driver-guides are all in constant communication with one another, and the sighting of a lion leads to rapid convergence of every vehicle within electronic earshot. The  animals don't seem to mind, how ever. We watched a mother and cub stroll between the Land Rovers as casually as a pedestrian jaywalking through the cars at a Manhattan intersection.</p>
        <p>In any case, Mr. Korda's solution -- staying in lodges that cost $660 to $1,000 a night -- seems a little like the solution to the bread shortage ascribed to Marie Antoinette: ''Qu'ils mangent de la brioche.''</p>
        <p>RALPH WESTON  Brookhaven, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
